result.execSummary:
The defendant Kimberly S. Sullivan was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Neglecting a Child (Consequence is Death), a class D felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.21(1)(d).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Case called at 10:19 am [Clerk SH] (Final Status Scheduling Conference)
Defendant Kimberly S. Sullivan in court with Attorney Jeffrey Jacob De La Rosa. Attorney Haley Johnson appears for the State of Wisconsin.
Atty De La Rosa informs the Court that they should move forward with the FSSC, but that he does not believe that settlement negotiations have been exhausted. Requests 24-48 hours to inform the Court if matter has been resolved. 
Atty Johnson: Agree with request
Counsel agree that Friday by 12:00 pm will be enough time to explore settlement discussions; Atty De La Rosa agrees to commuicate to the Court. 
Court informs parties that if the matter does settle, it would like to hear next week so it may use the scheduled trial dates for other events, likely Wednesday
Upon questioning of Atty De La Rosa, the Court approves a reserve judge taking plea, but not sentencing

Atty Johnson informs the Court that 2 witnesses have been removed from list; so have 15 witnesses, with 1 expert. Need at least 3 days for case in chief
Atty De La Rosa informs the Court that all witnesses are named on the State's witness list with an additional 3-4 possible, needing a day to day and half
Court informs parties that if matter shrinks to 4-5 days, then is likely to start this trial on Tuesday and run, Tuesday to Friday - but alert witnesses may begin on Tuesday

Atty De La Rosa informs the Court that there are No Miranda Goodchild Issues; No Motion to Admit has been filed, but statements are in discovery
Atty Johnson informs the Court that all statements have been made available in discovery; Court informs Atty Johnson that any statements not in discovery must be made available to the Court/Defense outside the presence of the jury, prior to introduction
Court discusses trial procedure with Atty Johnson and motion matters to be heard before trial
Atty Johnson informs the Court that she foresees no pretrial motions
Atty De La Rosa informs the Court that he did intend to file motion in limine today, but failed to bring today; are standard motions in limine. 
Upon questioning of the Court, Atty De La Rosa indicates he foresees no Daubert issues

2 alternates; 5 strikes each - 24 in the box
Court orders an additional 10 people be brought in for the jury panel
jurors make take notes and ask questions
lunch will likely be provided for jurors (30-45 minutes only for lunch)
Court informs parties that if case does not settle, the deadline for jury instructions is 2/24/16 end of business.
Court informs Miss Sullivan that noon on Friday is the last date for change in plea/settlement and that her bond continues.
Upon questioning of the Court, Atty Johnson confirms that she will be trying the case
Atty De La Rosa submits protective order re: discovery - Clerk provides copy to Atty De La Rosa & Atty Johnson

Case called at 2:32pm [mo]
Defendant Kimberly S. Sullivan in court with Attorney Jeffrey Jacob De La Rosa.   ADA Jeffrey Shock appears for the State of Wisconsin.

The Court discloses to Atty De La Rosa that it and ADA Shock had a conversation earlier regarding the Special Prosecutor assigned to this case and the the legality of allowing another prosecutor to appear on behalf of the Special Prosecutor for todays hearing only.
--ADA Shock indicates that he will be appearing for bond purposes only
--No Objection from Atty. De La Rosa regarding ADA Shock appearing for Attorney Necci at todays hearing
--ADA Shock will be appearing not as a member of the Jefferson CO. DA's office but as a special designee on behalf of Attorney Necci

The Court discloses that it knows Ms. Sullivan due to her former employment, and through the owner's of the establishment. Further, the Court indicates that this contact was only in the relationship of service provider/ customer. The Court finds no need to recuse or disqualify itself from this case or proceedings. 

Further the Court discloses that it has had contact with Ms. Sullivan's father and had a brief discussion about this case, prior to it becoming a case. The Court finds no need to recuse or disqualify itself from this case or proceedings. 

The Court discloses that in its former capacity as the Jefferson County (Assistant) District Attorney, that it did/did supervise attorneys that did prosecute Ms. Haag/Sullivan. The Court finds no need to recuse or disqualify itself from this case or proceedings. 

Ms. Sullivan provides an updated Ryder St. address; verifies date of birth
